                        <p class="m7">
                            <b>Procedural Programming  </b>
                            The very first programming framework a new developer would study is the procedural programming. The procedural code is basically the one that specifically advises a machine to perform a task using logical steps. This framework employs a top-down linear methodology and views data and procedures as two distinct entities. Procedural Programming, based on the notion of a procedure call, distinguishes the code into procedures, which are sometimes known as routines or functions, essentially comprising a series of actions to be performed.</br>Procedural programming can be used to implement a series of assertions that result in a response. Generally, different variables, various loops and other elements are used in this type of language which distinguishes it from functional programming language. Procedural language functions can influence variables, in addition to the value of the function returned.
                        </p>

                        <p class="m7">
                            <b>Functional Programming Language </b>
                            Functional programming is a programming framework where we attempt to connect everything in the form of purely mathematical functions. Functional programming is a declarative style of programming. The primary objective in this style is "what to fix" as opposed to an imperative approach where "how to fix" a problem is the primary objective. Rather than statements it incorporates expressions. To generate a value an expression is assessed, while a statement is performed to allocate variables. Functional programming language generally utilizes stored data, often excluding loops in lieu of repetitive functions. The main goal in functional programming is on the returning values of functions, so side effects and varying suggests that the storage state is strongly opposed.  Nevertheless, it may create algorithmic calls and alter those call parameters. This language makes it fairly easier to identify and solve intangible issues, however, the programming framework of a functional program is quite difficult to understand but it is much easier for the machine to run. 
                        </p>

